                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d228">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/12308: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="19" xml:id="d228fn19">The same to the Ambassador in Italy
                        as Department’s No. 1854, Nov. 22, 1918, 4 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-22T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 22, 1918—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6379. Your 5924, November 20. The Italian Ambassador was today orally informed
                    that the Department is disturbed at the reports showing Italian–Jugo-Slav
                    friction in the Adriatic and that this Government hoped that Italy would take no
                    step which would tend to increase such friction until all matters could be
                    frankly discussed at the coming Peace Conference. The Ambassador showed
                    Department a telegram just received from Sonnino, reporting a conversation with
                    the French Ambassador at Rome, at which it was agreed that the Italian and
                    Allied flags shall fly from all occupied places outside territory occupied by
                    Italy under the armistice.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
